llege London|accessdate=28 Nov 2018}}</ref>\n| mascot = \n| website = {{Official URL}}\n| logo = Imperial College London logo.svg\n| faculty = 4,390 {{small|(2018/19)}}<ref name=HESAstaff>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/staff/working-in-he#provider|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]] |title=Who's working in HE |accessdate=1 March 2020|at=Staff numbers by HE provider }}</ref>\n| staff = 4,075 {{small|(2016/17)}}<ref name=\"HESAstaff\"/>\n| affiliations = {{Plainlist}}\n* [[Association of Commonwealth Universities|ACU]]\n* [[Association of MBAs|AMBA]]\n* [[European University Association|EUA]]\n* [[G5 (universities)|G5]]\n* [[Global Alliance of Technological Universities]]\n* [[Golden triangle (universities)|Golden triangle]]\n* [[League of European Research Universities|LERU]]\n* [[MedCity (London)|MedCity]]\n* [[Russell Group]]\n* [[SES (universities)|SES]]\n{{Endplainlist}}\n| logo_size = 140px\n}}<!--Intro and history--><!--Join Lead Discussion - Talk Page-->'''Imperial College London''' (legally '''Imperial College of Science, Technology and Medicine''')<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/administration-and-support-services/secretariat/public/college-governance/charters-statutes-ordinances-regulations/charters-and-statutes/CHARTER---July-2007--(Rev--Nov-2014).pdf |title=Imperial College of Science, Technology and Medicine \u2013 Charter |publisher=Imperial College London }}</ref> is a [[public university|public]] [[research university]] in [[London]]. Dating back to the [[Royal College of Chemistry]]'s foundation in 1845, Imperial grew out of [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]]'s [[Albertopolis|vision]] of an area for culture, including the [[Royal Albert Hall]], [[Imperial Institute]], numerous museums, and the [[Royal College]]s that would go on to form the college.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.royalalberthall.com/about-the-hall/news/2016/july/prince-alberts-cultural-vision-and-the-history-of-south-kensington-what-is-albertopolis/|title=Prince Albert's cultural vision and the history of South Kensington: What is Albertopolis?|publisher=Royal Albert Hall|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-01-03}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/natural-sciences/departments/chemistry/about/our-history/chemistry-at-imperial/|title=Chemistry at Imperial|website=Imperial College London|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> In 1907, Imperial College was established by [[royal charter|Royal Charter]], merging the [[Royal College of Science]], [[Royal School of Mines]], and [[City and Guilds of London Institute|City and Guilds College]].<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com/LibraryDrawingsAndPhotographs/Albertopolis/TheStoryOf/ImperialCollege/CityAndGuildsCollege.aspx|title=City and Guilds College \u2500 Imperial College|website=architecture.com|publisher=Royal Institute of British Architects|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002165842/http://www.architecture.com/LibraryDrawingsAndPhotographs/Albertopolis/TheStoryOf/ImperialCollege/CityAndGuildsCollege.aspx|archive-date=2 October 2012|url-status=}}</ref>  In 1988, the [[Imperial College School of Medicine]] was formed by combining with [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital Medical School]]. In 2004, [[Queen Elizabeth II]] opened the [[Imperial College Business School]].\n\n<!--Campuses and organisation-->\nThe college focuses exclusively on science, technology, medicine and business. The college's main campus is located in [[South Kensington]], and it has an innovation campus in [[White City, London|White City]], a research field station at [[Silwood Park]], and teaching hospitals throughout London. The college was a member of the [[University of London]] from 1908, becoming independent on its centenary in 2007.<ref name=\"UoLHistRec\"/><ref name=\"GuardSplit\"/>  Imperial has an international community, with more than 59% of students from outside the UK and 140 countries represented on campus.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/best-universities/most-international-universities-world-2018|title=Most international universities in the world 2018: top 200|date=14 March 2018|work=[[Times Higher Education]]}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/study/international-students/|title=International students {{!}} Study|publisher=Imperial College London|access-date=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n<!--Academic profile and alumni-->\nIn 2019\u201320, Imperial is internationally ranked 9th in the ''[[QS World University Rankings]]'', 10th in the ''[[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]]'', 8th in ''[[Reuters - The World's Most Innovative Universities|Reuters The World's Most Innovative Universities]]'', and 24th in the ''[[Academic Ranking of World Universities]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2018|title=QS World University Rankings 2018|date=2017-02-01|website=Top Universities|language=en|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/world-ranking|title=World University Rankings|date=2018-09-26|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amers-reuters-ranking-innovative-univ-idUSKCN1ML0AZ|title=Reuters Top 100: The World's Most Innovative Universities \u2013 2018|date=2018-10-11|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-01-08|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/ARWU2018.html|title=ARWU World University Rankings 2018 {{!}} Academic Ranking of World Universities 2018 {{!}} Top 500 universities {{!}} Shanghai Ranking \u2013 2018|website=shanghairanking.com|access-date=2019-01-08}}</ref> Student, staff, and researcher affiliations include [[List of Nobel laureates by university affiliation|14 Nobel laureates]], [[List of Fields Medal winners by university affiliation|3 Fields Medalists]], [[List of Turing Award laureates by university affiliation|1 Turing Award winner]], 74 [[Royal Society|Fellows of the Royal Society]], 87 [[Royal Academy of Engineering|Fellows of the Royal Academy of Engineering]], and 85 [[Academy of Medical Sciences|Fellows of the Academy of Medical Sciences]].<ref name=\"Imperial.ac.uk2\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/introducing-imperial/our-people/award-winners/|title=Award winners &#124; Imperial College London|date=|website=imperial.ac.uk|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Prince Albert - Partridge 1840.jpg|thumb|upright|[[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]] was the main patron of the early [[Royal College]]s and the development of an [[Albertopolis|area of culture]] in South Kensington]]\n{{Main|History of Imperial College London}}\n\n=== 19th century ===\nThe earliest college that led to the formation of Imperial was the [[Royal College of Chemistry]], founded in 1845, with the support of [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]] and [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|parliament]].<ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/natural-sciences/departments/chemistry/about/our-history/chemistry-at-imperial/|title=Chemistry at Imperial|website=Imperial College London|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref>  This was merged in 1853 into what became known as the [[Royal School of Mines]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com/LibraryDrawingsAndPhotographs/Albertopolis/TheStoryOf/ImperialCollege/RoyalSchoolOfMines.aspx|title=Royal School of Mines \u2013 Imperial College|website=architecture.com|publisher=Royal Institute of British Architects|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120915014903/http://www.architecture.com/LibraryDrawingsAndPhotographs/Albertopolis/TheStoryOf/ImperialCollege/RoyalSchoolOfMines.aspx|archive-date=15 September 2012|url-status=}}</ref> The [[Imperial College School of Medicine|medical school]] has roots in many different schools across London, the oldest of which being [[Charing Cross Hospital Medical School]] which can be traced back to 1823, followed by teaching starting at [[Westminster Hospital]] in 1834, and [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]] in 1851.<ref name=\"timeline\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/history/college-developments/|title=A timeline of College developments|last=|first=|date=|website=imperial.ac.uk|publisher=Imperial College London|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ballantyne|first=John|date=August 2004|title=St Mary's: the History of a London Teaching Hospital|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of Medicine|volume=97|issue=8|pages=405\u2013406|issn=0141-0768|pmc=1079568|doi=10.1258/jrsm.97.8.405-a}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ezitis.myzen.co.uk/charingcross.html|title=Lost Hospitals of London|website=ezitis.myzen.co.uk|access-date=2018-12-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 1851, the [[The Great Exhibition|Great Exhibition]] was organised as an exhibition of [[culture]] and [[industry]] by [[Henry Cole]] and by Prince Albert, husband of the reigning monarch of the United Kingdom, [[Queen Victoria]].  An enormously popular and financial success, proceeds from the Great Exhibition were designated to develop an area for cultural and scientific advancement in [[South Kensington]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.chr.org.uk/Museums/albertopolis2.htm|title=Albertopolis \u2013 the wisdom of Prince Albert|last=|first=|date=|website=chr.org.uk|publisher=Cultural Heritage Resources|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> Within the next 6 years the [[Victoria and Albert Museum]] and [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]] had opened, joined by new facilities in 1871 for the Royal College of Chemistry and in 1881 for the Royal School of Mines, the opening of the [[Natural History Museum, London|Natural History Museum]] in 1881, and in 1888 the [[Imperial Institute]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vol38/pp233-247#h2-0003|title=Imperial College|last=|first=|date=|website=british-history.ac.uk|publisher=British History Online|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref>\n[[File:Commonwealth Institute QE1 35.jpg|thumb|left|The [[Commonwealth Institute|Imperial Institute]]]]\n\nIn 1881, the Normal School of Science was established in South Kensington under the leadership of [[Thomas Henry Huxley|Thomas Huxley]], taking over responsibility for the teaching of the natural sciences and agriculture from the Royal School of Mines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.architecture.com/LibraryDrawingsAndPhotographs/Albertopolis/TheStoryOf/ImperialCollege/RoyalCollegeOfScience.aspx|title=Royal College of Science \u2500 Imperial College|website=architecture.com|publisher=Royal Institute of British Architects|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121002170240/http://www.architecture.com/LibraryDrawingsAndPhotographs/Albertopolis/TheStoryOf/ImperialCollege/RoyalCollegeOfScience.aspx|archive-date=2 October 2012|url-status=}}</ref> The school was renamed the [[Royal College of Science]] by [[Royal Consent|royal consent]] in 1890.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=bWwKWnp9vaoC&pg=PA38#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Abbreviations|isbn=9780192800732|language=en|year=1992}}</ref> The Central Institution of the [[City and Guilds of London Institute]], was opened as a [[Mechanics' Institutes|technical education]] school on [[Exhibition Road]] by the [[George V|Prince of Wales]] in early 1885.<ref name=\":10\" />\n[[File:Royal-College-of-Science,-Imperial-College-Road.jpg|thumb|[[Royal College of Science]]]]\n\n===20th century===\nAt the start of the 20th century there was a concern that [[Great Britain|Britain]] was falling behind [[Germany]] in scientific and technical education. A departmental committee was set up at the [[Ministry of Education (United Kingdom)|Board of Education]] in 1904, to look into the future of the Royal College of Science. A report released in 1906 called for the establishment of an institution unifying the Royal College of Science and the Royal School of Mines, as well as \u2013 if agreement could be reached with the City and Guilds of London Institute \u2013 their Central Technical College.<ref name=\"bh\">{{cite book|url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/survey-london/vol38/pp233-247|title=Imperial College|date=1975|work=Survey of London: Volume 38, South Kensington Museums Area|publisher=London County Council|editor=F. H. W. Sheppard|pages=233\u2013247|via=british-history.ac.uk}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=46MOAQAAIAAJ&pg=RA1-PA16|pages=16\u201317|title=The Report of the Board of Education to the King's Most Excellent Majesty in Council for the Year 1905\u20131906|date=1906|publisher=HMSO}}</ref>\n\nOn 8 July 1907, [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] granted a [[Royal Charter]] establishing the Imperial College of Science and Technology. This incorporated the Royal School of Mines and the Royal College of Science. It also made provisions for the City and Guilds College to join once conditions regarding its governance were met, as well as for Imperial to become a college of the [[University of London]].<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|issue=1959|volume=76|url=https://archive.org/details/paper-doi-10_1038_076056a0|pages=56\u201357|date=16 May 1907|title=Imperial College of Science and Technology|doi=10.1038/076056a0|bibcode=1907Natur..76...56.|doi-access=free}}</ref> The college joined the University of London on 22 July 1908, with the City and Guilds College joining in 1910.<ref name=\"UoLHistRec\">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vyPiAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA85|title=University of London, the Historical Record|date=1912|publisher=University of London Press|page=85}}</ref><ref name=\":10\" /> The main campus of Imperial College was constructed beside the buildings of the [[Imperial Institute]], the new building for the Royal College of Science having opened across from it in 1906, and the foundation stone for the Royal School of Mines building being laid by [[Edward VII|King Edward VII]] in July 1909.<ref name=\"bh\" />\n\nAs students at Imperial had to study separately for London degrees, in January 1919, students and alumni voted for a petition to make Imperial a university with its own degree awarding powers, independent of the University of London.<ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|url=https://archive.org/details/jstor-1643261/page/n1|title=The London Imperial College of Science and Technology|pages=209\u2013210|date=28 February 1919|volume=XLIX| issue=1261|bibcode=1919Sci....49..209.|doi=10.1126/science.49.1261.209}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|journal=[[Nature (journal)|Nature]]|issue=2632|volume=105|url=https://archive.org/details/paper-doi-10_1038_105173a0/page/n1|pages=173\u2013175|date=16 May 1907|title=The Imperial College of Science and Technology|doi=10.1038/105173a0|doi-access=free}}</ref> In response, the University of London changed its regulations in 1925 so that the courses taught only at Imperial would be examined by the university, enabling students to gain a BSc.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/centenary/timeline/1920.shtml#college|title=Imperial College 1920\u20131929|publisher=Imperial College|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:Imperial College Royal School of Mines.jpg|thumb|left|[[Royal School of Mines]]]]\n\nIn October 1945, [[George VI|King George VI]] and [[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Queen Elizabeth]] visited Imperial to commemorate the centenary of the Royal College of Chemistry, which was the oldest of the institutions that united to form Imperial College. \"Commemoration Day\", named after this visit, is held every October as the university's main graduation ceremony.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/centenary/timeline/1940.shtml#college|title=Imperial College 1940\u20131949|publisher=Imperial College|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/188666/imperial-celebrates-newest-graduates-commemoration-day/|title=Imperial celebrates its newest graduates at Commemoration Day 2018|publisher=Imperial College|accessdate=21 January 2019}}</ref> The college also acquired a biology field station at [[Silwood Park]] near [[Ascot, Berkshire]] in 1947<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=2BpqDQAAQBAJ&pg=PA760&lpg=PA760&dq=silwood+park+1947#v=onepage&q=silwood%20park%201947&f=false|title=The History of Imperial College London, 1907\u20132007: Higher Education and Research in Science, Technology, and Medicine|last=Gay|first=Hannah|date=2007|publisher=World Scientific|isbn=9781860947087|language=en}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the second world war, there was again concern that Britain was falling behind in science \u2013 this time to the United States. The Percy Report of 1945 and Barlow Committee in 1946 called for a \"British [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT]]\"-equivalent, backed by influential scientists as politicians of the time, including [[Lord Cherwell]], Sir [[Lawrence Bragg]] and Sir [[Edward Victor Appleton|Edward Appleton]].<ref name=\"bocock\">{{cite journal|author=Jean Bocock |author2=Lewis Baston |author3=Peter Scott |author4=David Smith|year=2003|title=American influence on British higher education: science, technology, and the problem of university expansion, 1945\u20131963|journal=Minerva|volume=41|issue=4|pages=327\u2013346|doi=10.1023/B:MINE.0000005154.25610.b2|jstor=41821255}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qCRFBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA22|title=Making Policy in British Higher Education 1945-2011|author=Michael Shattock|date=1 October 2012|publisher=McGraw-Hill Education (UK)|isbn=9780335241873}}</ref> The [[University Grants Committee (United Kingdom)|University Grants Committee]] strongly opposed however,<ref name=\"bocock\" /> and so a compromise was reached in 1953, where Imperial would remain within the university, but double in size over the next ten years.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/Commons/1952-06-11/debates/ffbd1622-6f13-4927-9e07-7dec170ee574/HigherTechnologicalEducation(GovernmentPolicy)|title=Higher Technological Education (Government Policy)|date=11 June 1952|work=Hansard|accessdate=22 January 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://hansard.parliament.uk/commons/1953-01-29/debates/efdd76ab-4f52-47cc-b094-66f297bb6980/ImperialCollegeOfScienceAndTechnology(Expansion)|title=Imperial College Of Science And Technology (Expansion)|author=John Boyd-Carpenter|date=29 January 1953|work=Hansard|author-link=John Boyd-Carpenter}}</ref> The expansion led to a number of new buildings being erected. These included the Hill building in 1957 and the Physics building in 1960, and the completion of the East Quadrangle, built in four stages between 1959 and 1965. The building work also meant the demolition of the City and Guilds College building in 1962\u201363, and the Imperial Institute's building by 1967.<ref name=\"VCH\">{{cite book|chapter-url=https://www.british-history.ac.uk/vch/middx/vol1/pp345-359#h3-0004|pages=345\u2013359|work=A History of the County of Middlesex: Volume 1, Physique, Archaeology, Domesday, Ecclesiastical Organization, the Jews, Religious Houses, Education of Working Classes To 1870, Private Education From Sixteenth Century|chapter=The University of London: The Constituent Colleges|title=The Imperial College of Science and Technology|year=1969|publisher=[[Victoria County History]]|editor1= J S Cockburn |editor2=H P F King |editor3=K G T McDonnell|via=British History Online}}</ref> Opposition from the [[Royal Fine Arts Commission]] and others meant that [[Queen's Tower, London|Queen's Tower]] was retained, with work carried out between 1966 and 1968 to make it free standing.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Queen's Tower|publisher=Imperial College|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/history/queens-tower/|accessdate=29 January 2019}}</ref> New laboratories for biochemistry, established with the support of a \u00a3350,000 grant from the [[Wolfson Foundation]], were opened by the [[Elizabeth II|Queen]] in 1965.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wolfson.org.uk/media/2411/wf_sixty-years-of-philanthropy.pdf|pages=29, 57|title=The Wolfson Foundation 1955\u20132015: Sixty Years of Philanthropy|publisher=The Wolfson Foundation|date=2015|access-date=17 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202001135/http://www.wolfson.org.uk/media/2411/wf_sixty-years-of-philanthropy.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"1960s\">{{Cite web |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/centenary/timeline/1960.shtml |title= Imperial College \u2013 Centenary website \u2013 Timeline \u2013 1960\u20131969 |website= www.imperial.ac.uk |access-date= 19 December 2016 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Imperial College Business School opened by Queen Elizabeth II.png|alt=|thumb|[[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] opening the [[Imperial College Business School]]]]\nIn 1988, Imperial merged with [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]] under the Imperial College Act 1988. Amendments to the [[royal charter]] changed the formal name of the institution to ''The Imperial College of Science, Technology and Medicine'' and made St Mary's a constituent college.<ref name=\"charternote\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/administration-and-support-services/secretariat/public/college-governance/charters-statutes-ordinances-regulations/charters-and-statutes/CHARTER---July-2007--(Rev--Nov-2014).pdf|publisher=Imperial College|title=Charter and Statutes|at=Explanatory note|accessdate=2 February 2019}}</ref> This was followed by mergers with the [[National Heart and Lung Institute]] in 1995 and the [[Charing Cross and Westminster Medical School]], Royal Postgraduate Medical School (RPMS) and the Institute of Obstetrics and Gynaecology in 1997, with the [[Imperial College Act 1997]] formally establishing the Imperial College School of Medicine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/publications/reporterarchive/0048/news01.htm|title=WEST LONDON MEDICINE \u2013 PAST AND FUTURE|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial College London|access-date=2018-06-24}}</ref>\n\n=== 21st century ===\nIn 2003, Imperial was granted degree-awarding powers in its own right by the [[Privy Council of the United Kingdom|Privy Council]]. In 2004, the [[Imperial College Business School]] and a new main entrance on Exhibition Road were opened by [[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]].<ref name=\"A timeline of College Developments2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/history/college-developments/|title=A timeline of College Developments|website=Imperial College London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/newsandeventspggrp/imperialcollege/newssummary/news_20-8-2008-11-23-23?newsid=42715|title=New identity for Imperial College Business School|publisher=Imperial College London|accessdate=20 June 2017}}</ref> The [[UK Energy Research Centre]] was also established in 2004 and opened its headquarters at Imperial. On 9 December 2005, Imperial announced that it would commence negotiations to secede from the University of London.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.imperial.ac.uk/P7134.htm |title= Imperial College London \u2013 Imperial College London to begin negotiations to withdraw from the University of London |publisher= Imperial.ac.uk |date=9 December 2005 |accessdate= 16 June 2011}}</ref> Imperial became fully independent of the University of London in July 2007.<ref name=\"GuardSplit\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2006/oct/05/highereducation.administration|title=Imperial College splits from University of London |work=The Guardian|accessdate=27 November 2015|date=5 October 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.comp.nus.edu.sg/~wongls/icaas-web/news/stnews-2jan06/index.html |title=Imperial College top choice for Singaporean students |publisher=Comp.nus.edu.sg |accessdate=23 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110611055656/http://www.comp.nus.edu.sg/~wongls/icaas-web/news/stnews-2jan06/index.html |archivedate=11 June 2011 |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.london.ac.uk/495.html |title= University of London: Updated position statement re: Imperial College London |publisher= London.ac.uk |accessdate= 16 June 2011 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20061210104621/http://www.london.ac.uk/495.html |archivedate= 10 December 2006 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, Imperial and [[King's College London]] joined the UK Centre for Medical Research and Innovation as partners with a commitment of \u00a340 million each to the project. The centre was later renamed the [[Francis Crick Institute]] and opened on 9 November 2016. It the largest single biomedical laboratory in Europe. The college began moving into the new White City campus in 2016, with the launching of the Innovation Hub.<ref name=\"WhiteCity\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/175572/imperial-launches-innovation-white-city/|title=Imperial launches its new hub for innovation at White City|website=Imperial News|publisher=Imperial College London|language=en|access-date=2019-04-04}}</ref> This was followed by the opening of the Molecular Sciences Research Hub for the [[Department of Chemistry, Imperial College London|Department of Chemistry]], officially opened by [[Mayor of London]], [[Sadiq Khan]] in 2019.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n==Campuses==\n[[File:Imperial College Business School.jpg|thumb|Main entrance at South Kensington]]\n\n=== South Kensington ===\nImperial's main campus is based in [[Kensington|South Kensington]].  Notable buildings include the [[Royal College of Science]], the [[Royal School of Mines]], the [[Imperial College Business School|Business School]], and the Queen's Tower, which sits is at the heart of the campus. As part of [[Albertopolis]], a cultural centre based on the vision of [[Albert, Prince Consort|Prince Albert]], the campus is surrounded by many of London's most popular cultural attractions including the [[Royal Albert Hall]] and [[Kensington Palace]], museums including the [[Natural History Museum]], [[Victoria and Albert Museum]], and [[Science Museum (London)|Science Museum]], and institutions such as the [[Royal College of Art]], the [[Royal College of Music]], and the [[National Art Library]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.mit.edu/2018/mit-expands-multi-departmental-partnership-imperial-college-london-0222|title=MIT expands partnership with Imperial College London|work=MIT News|access-date=2018-05-12}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-london-43417939|title=London's top tourist attractions see visitor numbers fall|date=16 March 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe campus has many restaurants and caf\u00e9s run by the college,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/admin-services/food-and-drink/|title=Food and drink|website=Imperial College London}}</ref> and contains much of the student accommodation, including the Prince's Garden Halls, and [[Beit Hall]], home to the [[Imperial College Union|college union]], which runs student pubs, a nightclub, and a cinema on site. To the north lie [[Kensington Gardens]] and [[Hyde Park, London|Hyde Park]], which are within easy walking distance from the college, and provide green spaces and sports facilities which many of the student clubs take advantage of.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.union.ic.ac.uk/acc/tennis/|title=IC Tennis \u2013 Imperial College Lawn Tennis Club|date=28 August 2018}}</ref>[[File:Entrance place and passage, White City North Campus.jpg|thumb|White City Campus]]\n\n=== White City ===\nA second major campus has started opening in [[White City, London|White City]], to the west of the main campus, providing an innovation hub for the college, including research facilities and commercialisation space, as well as postgraduate accommodation.<ref>{{citation|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/b6317348-1c96-11e4-98d8-00144feabdc0,Authorised=false.html?siteedition=uk&_i_location=http%3A%2F%2Fwww.ft.com%2Fcms%2Fs%2F0%2Fb6317348-1c96-11e4-98d8-00144feabdc0.html%3Fsiteedition%3Duk&_i_referer=&classification=conditional_standard&iab=barrier-app|title=Imperial unveils details of \u00a33bn campus extension|first=Claer|last=Barrett|date=5 August 2014|via=Financial Times}}</ref> The chemistry department moved much of its research to the new Molecular Sciences Research Hub on the campus in 2018,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/articles/2018-11-30-white-city-woes/|title=White City Woes|last=Djaba|first=Andy|website=felixonline.co.uk|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> with further departments and industry partners moving to the campus and surrounding area over the coming years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.standard.co.uk/business/novartis-joins-rush-of-science-companies-moving-to-white-city-a4002746.html|title=Novartis joins rush of science companies moving to White City|date=2018-11-28|website=Evening Standard|language=en|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> The campus is also home to the Invention Rooms, a college [[hackerspace]] and community outreach centre.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/articles/2017-11-03-college-reaches-out-to-white-city-community-with-invention-rooms/|title=College reaches out to White City community with Invention Rooms|last=Fyles|first=Fred S.|website=felixonline.co.uk|language=en-us|access-date=2018-12-24}}</ref> The area hosts a number of biotechnology companies in the Imperial White City Incubator and the Open Cell biotech hub.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lbhf.gov.uk/articles/news/2018/07/open-cell-launches-affordable-biotech-hub-shepherds-bush|title=Open Cell launches affordable biotech hub in Shepherds Bush|date=31 July 2018|website=Hammersmith & Fulham Council|language=en|access-date=31 July 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/thinkspace/partners-and-services/imperial-white-city-incubator/|title=Imperial White City Incubator|work=Imperial College London|accessdate=27 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Silwood Park ===\nSilwood Park is a postgraduate campus of Imperial located in the village of Sunninghill near [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]] in Berkshire. The [[Silwood Park]] campus includes a centre for research and teaching in ecology, evolution, and conservation set in 100 ha of parkland where ecological field experiments are conducted, and contains student halls for students studying for a degree on the site.\n\n=== Hospitals ===\nImperial has teaching hospitals across London which are used by the [[Imperial College School of Medicine|School of Medicine]] for undergraduate clinical teaching and medical research. All are based around college-affiliated hospitals, and also provide catering and sport facilities. College libraries are located on each campus, including the Fleming library at St Mary's.<ref>{{cite web |title=St Mary's Fleming Library |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/admin-services/library/use-the-library/our-libraries/st-marys-fleming-library/ |publisher=Imperial College London |accessdate=26 December 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Organisation and administration==\n=== Faculties and departments ===\nImperial is organised through a network of faculties and departments:<ref>{{cite web|title=Faculties and departments|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/Faculties-and-departments/|publisher=Imperial College London|accessdate=21 April 2018}}</ref>\n\n{{Columns\n| colwidth =    20vw\n| col1 =\n; [[Imperial College Faculty of Engineering|Faculty of Engineering]]\n* Aeronautical Engineering\n* Bioengineering\n* [[Department of Chemical Engineering, Imperial College London|Chemical Engineering]]\n* [[Department of Civil and Environmental Engineering, Imperial College London|Civil & Environmental Engineering]]\n* [[Department of Computing, Imperial College London|Computing]]\n* [[Dyson School of Design Engineering]]\n* Earth Science & Engineering\n* Electrical & Electronic Engineering\n* [[Department of Materials, Imperial College London|Materials]]\n* [[Department of Mechanical Engineering, Imperial College London|Mechanical Engineering]]\n| col2 =\n; [[Imperial College Faculty of Natural Sciences|Faculty of Natural Sciences]]\n* [[Centre for Environmental Policy]]\n* [[Department of Chemistry, Imperial College London|Chemistry]]\n* Life Sciences\n* Mathematics\n* [[Blackett Laboratory|Physics]]\n| col3 = \n; [[Imperial College Faculty of Medicine|Faculty of Medicine]]\n* Brain Sciences \n* Immunology and Inflammation\n* Infectious Disease\n* Metabolism, Digestion and Reproduction\n* Surgery and Cancer\n* Institute of Clinical Sciences\n* National Heart and Lung Institute\n* School of Public Health\n| col4 =\n; [[Imperial College Business School]]\n* Finance\n* Innovation & Entrepreneurship\n* Management\n|gapbetween=2em}}\n[[File:53_Princes_Garden.tif|thumb|upright|The Brevan Howard Centre for Financial Analysis]]\n\n=== Global institutes ===\nImperial hosts global centres to promote inter-disciplinary work:\n\n* Energy Futures Laboratory\n* Gandhi Centre for Inclusive Innovation\n*[[Grantham Institute for Climate Change]]\n* Institute for Security Science & Technology\n* Centre for Health Economics & Policy Innovation\n* Brevan Howard Centre for Financial Analysis & Technology\n* Global Entrepreneurship & Development Index\n*[[Data Science Institute]]\n* Institute for Molecular Science and Engineering\n*[[Francis Crick Institute]]\n\n=== Academic centres ===\n\nImperial College also houses two academic centres, formerly the Department of Humanities, offering teaching to undergraduate and postgraduate students in modern and historical languages, arts and humanities subjects, social sciences and other subjects which fall outside of the standard remit of science, technology and medicine. The aim of these centres is to provide training in study skills, such as the acquisition of English language proficiency, but also to encourage innovatory and interdisciplinary approaches to science, technology and medicine, which might make use of study of the arts, humanities, languages and social sciences. The academic centres are the:\n\n* Centre for Academic English\n* Centre for Languages, Culture and Communication\n\nThe Centre for Languages, Culture and Communication also operates as Imperial College London's adult education centre, offering evening class courses in the arts, humanities, languages and sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/evening-classes|title=Evening classes and lunchtime learning|work=Imperial College London|accessdate=2 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Governance===\n[[File:Imperial College Faculty Building 2005.jpg|thumb|The Faculty Building, designed by [[Norman Foster]]]]\n{{main|President and Rector of Imperial College London}}\n\nThe highest academic official of Imperial College London is the President, formerly known as the Rector. The [[President (college)|President]] is the [[chief executive]], elected by the Council of the college and Chairman of the Senate.<ref>{{Citation | url = http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/aboutimperial/imperial_people/pastrectors | title = Past Rectors | publisher = Imperial College London | accessdate = 2009-03-21}}</ref> The position has been held by [[Alice Gast]], an American chemical engineer, since September 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/138926/professor-alice-gast-become-sixteenth-head/|title=Professor Alice Gast to become sixteenth head and first woman to lead Imperial &#124; Imperial News &#124; Imperial College London|website=Imperial News}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, the additional post of [[Provost (education)|Provost]] was created. [[James Stirling (physicist)|James Stirling]] became the first Provost of Imperial College London in August 2013.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/newsandeventspggrp/imperialcollege/newssummary/news_12-12-2012-15-20-50 | title = James Stirling to be Imperial's first Provost | publisher = Imperial College London | date = 12 December 2012 | accessdate = 14 January 2013}}</ref> He was succeeded as Provost by [[Ian Walmsley]] in September 2018.\n\nThe council is the governing body of Imperial, it consists of 23 members including the Chairman, the President, the Provost, the President of the Imperial College Union, 4 members of senior staff, and between 9 and 13 lay members who are not employees of Imperial. The current Chair is [[Philip Dilley|Sir Philip Dilley]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Composition and Membership|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/admin-services/secretariat/college-governance/governance-structure/council/about-council/composition/|publisher=Imperial College London|accessdate=14 January 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Finances and endowment ===\n[[File:Royal Albert Hall Crop, London - Nov 2012.jpg|thumb|Graduation ceremonies take place in the [[Royal Albert Hall]]]]\nIn 2017/18, Imperial had a consolidated income of \u00a31,033.0 million. It has the [[List of UK universities by endowment|seventh largest endowment]] of any university in the United Kingdom, and the second largest of the universities in London.<ref name=\"AR2018-19\" /> The college's endowment is sub-divided into three distinct portfolios:\n\n* Unitised Scheme \u2013 a unit trust vehicle for the college, Faculties and Departments to invest endowments and unfettered income to produce returns for the long term\n* Non-Core Property \u2013 a portfolio containing around 120 operational and developmental properties which the college has determined are not core to the academic mission\n* Strategic Asset Investments \u2013 containing the college's shareholding in [[Imperial Innovations]] and other restricted equity holdings.<ref name=\"AR2018-19\" />\n\n=== Affiliations and partnerships ===\nImperial is a member of the [[Association of Commonwealth Universities]], [[European University Association]], [[Global Alliance of Technological Universities]], [[League of European Research Universities]] and the [[Russell Group]]. It is a founding member of the Imperial College [[academic health sciences centre]], the [[Francis Crick Institute]] and [[MedCity (London)|MedCity]].\n\nImperial is a long-term partner of the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], with the first formal large-scale collaboration agreement dating back to 1944 as part of the [[World War II]] scientific effort.<ref name=\"Imperial College and 'M.I.T.'\">{{Cite journal|date=1944-01-01|title=Imperial College and 'M.I.T.'|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/153104b0|journal=Nature|language=en|volume=153|issue=3873|pages=104\u2013104|doi=10.1038/153104b0|issn=1476-4687|doi-access=free}}</ref> The two institutions still share a strong bond with exchange programs for their students and academic staff.<ref name=\":12\" /><ref name=\":13\" />\n\n==Academic profile==\n===Rankings===\n{{Infobox UK university rankings\n| QS_W = 9\n| QS_N = 4\n| THE_W = 10\n| THE_N = 3\n| ARWU_W = 24\n| ARWU_N = 4\n| LINE_1 = 1\n| Complete = 5\n| The_Guardian = 7\n| Times/Sunday_Times = 4\n| LINE_2 = 0\n| TEF = Gold\n}} \n'''World & Europe'''\n\nImperial is ranked 10th globally by the 2020 [[Times Higher Education World University Rankings]],<ref>{{cite magazine|title=World University Rankings 2020|magazine=[[Times Higher Education]]|accessdate=5 October 2019|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2020/world-ranking#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats}}</ref> as well as 3rd in Europe and in the UK after Oxford and Cambridge in their 2019 European universities ranking.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/best-universities/best-universities-europe|title=Best universities in Europe|date=2018-11-21|website=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref> Within the 2019 subject rankings, Imperial is ranked 4th globally in the clinical, pre-clinical and health category,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=World University Rankings 2019 by subject: clinical, pre-clinical and health|magazine=[[Times Higher Education]]|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/subject-ranking/clinical-pre-clinical-health#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> 11th in physical sciences,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=World University Rankings 2019 by subject: physical sciences|magazine=[[Times Higher Education]]|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/subject-ranking/physical-sciences#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> 11th in computer science,<ref>{{cite magazine|title=World University Rankings 2019 by subject: computer science|magazine=[[Times Higher Education]]|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/subject-ranking/computer-science#!/page/0/length/25/sort_by/rank/sort_order/asc/cols/stats|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> 12th in engineering and technology<ref>{{cite magazine|title=World University Rankings 2019 by subject: engineering and technology|magazine=[[Times Higher Education]]|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/subject-ranking/engineering-and-IT|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref> and 14th in life sciences.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=World University Rankings 2019 by subject: life sciences|magazine=[[Times Higher Education]]|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/world-university-rankings/2019/subject-ranking/engineering-and-IT|accessdate=24 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe college is ranked 8th worldwide by the 2019 [[QS World University Rankings|QS World University Ranking]],<ref>{{cite web|title=QS World University Rankings 2019|publisher=Top Universities|date=2018-08-28|url=https://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/world-university-rankings/2019|accessdate=2018-06-13}}</ref> as well as 4th in Europe, and 1st in London.\n\nImperial is ranked 3rd in Europe, and 1st in London by the 2019 [[U.S. News & World Report Best Global University Ranking|U.S. News & World Report Global Ranking]].<ref name=\":3\">{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/education/best-global-universities/search?region=europe&subject=&name=|title=Top Universities in Europe &#124; US News Best Global Universities|date=28 October 2014|publisher=Usnews.com|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''National'''[[File:Imperial Institute Tower c1960 - geograph.org.uk - 132052.jpg|alt=|thumb|upright|[[Queen's Tower, London|Queen's Tower]]]]\nImperial is ranked 4th in the 2019 Times Higher Education \"Table of Tables\" which combines the results of the 3 main domestic league tables.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/table-tables-university-cambridge-top-fifth-year-running|title=THE 'Table of Tables' 2016: University of Cambridge top for fifth year running|date=15 October 2015|work=Times Higher Education|author=Chris Havergal}}</ref> In the 2019 Complete University Guide, all 14 of the subjects offered by Imperial were ranked top 10 nationally meaning it was one of three universities in the UK (along with Cambridge and Oxford) to have all subjects ranked in the top 10.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/imperial-college-london/performance|title=League Table Performance \u2013 Imperial College London|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\n'''Innovation'''\n\nIn 2018, [[Reuters - The World's Most Innovative Universities]] ranked Imperial 1st in [[innovation]] in the UK, and 2nd in Europe behind [[KU Leuven]].<ref name=\":0\">{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-amers-reuters-ranking-innovative-univ/reuters-top-100-the-worlds-most-innovative-universities-2018-idUSKCN1ML0AZ|title=Reuters|date=11 October 2018|newspaper=Reuters}}</ref>  In 2019, QS ranked Imperial 1st for [[MBA|MBA's]] in [[entrepreneurship]] in Europe, and 2nd in the world behind [[Stanford University|Stanford]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.topmba.com/mba-rankings/specialization/entrepreneurship/2019|title=MBA by Specialization \u2013 Entrepreneurship 2019|date=2019-03-15|website=TopMBA.com|language=en|access-date=2019-03-27}}</ref>\n\n'''Career Prospects'''\n\nAccording to both the 2019 Guardian University Guide and the Complete University Guide, students are ranked 1st for employment prospects among UK universities.<ref>{{cite web|title=Career University Guide|url=http://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Graduate+Prospects&v=wide&y=2016|website=Career Prospects}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?o=Graduate%20Prospects|title=Top UK University League Tables and Rankings 2020|website=thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk|language=en-gb|access-date=2019-05-22}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2018, the Guardian notes that Imperial graduates pick up the highest salaries in the UK in the first year after graduation, earning around a fifth more than students leaving Oxford and Cambridge.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2018/sep/24/graduates-of-imperial-college-beat-oxbridge-on-earnings|title=Graduates of Imperial College beat Oxbridge on earnings|last=Collinson|first=Patrick|date=2018-09-23|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-05-22|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\nA 2018 [[Department for Education]] report found that Imperial boosted female graduates earnings 31.3% above the average female graduate, and male graduates similarly saw a 25.3% increase in earnings above the average male graduate.<ref>{{cite web |title=Undergraduate degrees: relative labour market returns (Table 7: HEI \u2013 conditional impact on earnings five years after graduation) |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/undergraduate-degrees-relative-labour-market-returns |publisher=Department for Education |accessdate=17 December 2018}}</ref> The 2019 Department for Education statistics found that 5 years after graduation Imperial mathematics and computing graduates were among the UK's ten highest income degrees.<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education-and-careers/0/what-highest-paying-degrees-uk-top-graduate-salary-britain/|title=Britain's highest paying degrees, according to UK graduate salaries|last=Kirk|first=Ashley|date=2019-08-14|work=The Telegraph|access-date=2019-10-05|last2=Scott|first2=Patrick|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref>\n\nThe [[The New York Times|New York Times]] ranked Imperial College as one of the top 10 most-welcomed universities by the global job market in 2012.<ref>{{cite news|title=What the job market wants|url=https://www.nytimes.com/imagepages/2012/10/25/world/asia/25iht-sreducemerging25-graphic.html|accessdate=7 February 2013|newspaper=The New York Times|date=25 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Research===\nImperial submitted a total of 1,257 staff across 14 units of assessment to the 2014 [[Research Excellence Framework]] (REF) assessment.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/ref-2014-winners-who-performed-best/2017591.article|title=REF 2014 winners: who performed best?|accessdate=5 April 2015|work=Times Higher Education|date=18 December 2014}}</ref> This found that 91% of Imperial's research is \u201cworld-leading\u201d (46% achieved the highest possible 4* score) or \u201cinternationally excellent\u201d (44% achieved 3*), giving an overall GPA of 3.36.<ref name=\":9\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/research-and-innovation/about-imperial-research/ref/results/|title=Results|website=Imperial College London|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-05-19}}</ref><ref name=\"REFranking\">{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/download?ac=26855|title=Overall ranking of institutions including power market share|accessdate=5 April 2015|work=Times Higher Education|date=18 December 2014}}</ref> In rankings produced by ''Times Higher Education'' based upon the REF results Imperial was ranked 2nd overall.<ref name=\":9\" /><ref name=\"REFranking\" /> Imperial is also widely known to have been a critical contributor of the discovery of [[penicillin]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/college.asp?P=2590|title=Imperial College London \u2013 Fleming's early research is honoured|last=|first=|website=imperial.ac.uk|date=1999|access-date=2019-11-29}}{{dead link|date=March 2020|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref> the invention of [[Fiber Optics|fiber optics]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=5UtHAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA22&lpg=PA22&dq=imperial+college+invention+optic+fiber#v=onepage|title=Fiber Optic Video Transmission: The Complete Guide|last=Goff|first=David|date=2013-10-08|publisher=CRC Press|isbn=978-1-136-02490-0|location=|pages=22|language=en}}</ref> and the development of [[holography]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbvaopenmind.com/en/science/leading-figures/dennis-gabor-father-of-holography/|title=Dennis Gabor, \"Father of Holography\"|last=Bel\u00e9ndez|first=Augusto|date=2015-06-05|website=OpenMind|language=en-US|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> The college promotes research commercialisation, partly through its dedicated [[technology transfer]] company, [[Imperial Innovations]], which has given rise to a large number of [[spin-out]] companies based on academic research.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperialinnovations.co.uk/about/background/|title=Background to the Group \u2013 Imperial Innovations|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160731103858/http://www.imperialinnovations.co.uk/about/background/|archivedate=31 July 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thememo.com/2015/11/30/imperial-innovations-imperial-college-turning-innovation-into-cash/|title=How Imperial College is turning innovation into cash|date=30 November 2015|access-date=17 July 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820074154/https://www.thememo.com/2015/11/30/imperial-innovations-imperial-college-turning-innovation-into-cash/|archive-date=20 August 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref> Imperial College has a long-term partnership with the [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology]], that dates back from [[World War II]].<ref name=\"Imperial College and 'M.I.T.'\"/><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/185057/mit-imperial-launch-unparalleled-student-exchange/|title=MIT and Imperial launch 'unparalleled' student exchange {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|work=Imperial News|access-date=2018-03-21|language=en-GB}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite news|url=https://news.mit.edu/2018/mit-expands-multi-departmental-partnership-imperial-college-london-0222|title=MIT expands partnership with Imperial College London|work=MIT News|access-date=2018-03-21}}</ref> The [[United States]] is the college's top collaborating foreign country, with more than 15,000 articles co-authored by Imperial and U.S.-based authors over the last 10 years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/introducing-imperial/global-imperial/usa-and-canada/|title=USA and Canada {{!}} About {{!}} Imperial College London|website=imperial.ac.uk|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, the mathematics department of Imperial and the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|French National Center for Scientific Research]] launched UMI [[Abraham de Moivre]] at Imperial, a joint research laboratory of mathematics focused on unsolved problems and bridging [[United Kingdom|British]] and [[France|French]] scientific communities.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www2.cnrs.fr/en/3049.htm|title=Imperial College London and CNRS create joint laboratory to bring world's best mathematicians together \u2013 CNRS Web site \u2013 CNRS|last=ARTIFICA|website=www2.cnrs.fr|language=fr|access-date=2018-05-17}}</ref> The [[Fields Medal|Fields medallists]] [[C\u00e9dric Villani]] and [[Martin Hairer]] hosted the launch presentation.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/184039/fields-medal-winners-launch-mathematics-laboratory/|title=Fields Medal winners launch new mathematics laboratory|last=|first=|date=|work=Imperial News|access-date=2018-05-17|publisher=Imperial College London|language=en-GB}}</ref> In October 2018, Imperial College launched the Imperial Cancer Research UK Center, a research collaboration that aims to find innovative ways to improve the precision of cancer treatments, inaugurated by former [[Vice President of the United States]] [[Joe Biden]] as part of his Biden Cancer Initiative.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://crukimperialcentre.co.uk/|title=CRUK Imperial Center Website|last=|first=|date=|website=crukimperialcentre.co.uk|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/188531/joe-biden-delivers-inaugural-cancer-research/|title=Joe Biden delivers inaugural cancer research lecture at Imperial|last=|first=|date=|website=Imperial News|publisher=Imperial College London|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>\n\nImperial was one of the ten leading contributors to the NASA [[InSight|InSight Mars lander]] which landed on planet [[Mars]] in November 2018, with the college logo appearing on the craft.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mepag.jpl.nasa.gov/meeting/2016-10/04Banerdt_InSight.pdf|title=InSight Status Report|last=W. Bruce Banerdt|date=6 October 2016|website=|publisher=Jet Propulsion Laboratory|access-date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://mars.nasa.gov/raw_images/1567?site=insight|title=Sol 26: Instrument Deployment Camera (IDC)|last=mars.nasa.gov|website=NASA's InSight Mars Lander|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> InSight's Seismic Experiment for Interior Structure, developed at Imperial, measured the first likely [[marsquake]] reading in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.space.com/insight-mars-lander-first-marsquake.html|title=Marsquake! NASA's InSight Lander Feels Its 1st Red Planet Tremor|last=Science|first=Meghan Bartels 2019-04-23T19:19:28Z|last2=Astronomy|website=Space.com|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ox.ac.uk/news/2019-04-26-first-%E2%80%98marsquake%E2%80%99-captured-uk-sensors|title=First 'Marsquake' captured by UK sensors {{!}} University of Oxford|website=ox.ac.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/189229/marsquake-sensor-lands-safely-red-planet/|title=Marsquake sensor lands safely on Red Planet {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=Imperial College|date=|website=Imperial News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> In 2019, it was revealed that the [[Blackett Laboratory]] would be constructing an instrument for the [[European Space Agency]] [[Solar Orbiter]] in a mission to study the [[Sun]], which launched in February 2020.<ref name=\":15\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/193499/solar-orbiter-spacecraft-heads-launch-site/|title=Solar Orbiter spacecraft heads to launch site on its way to the Sun {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|date=|website=Imperial News|language=en|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.space.com/solar-orbiter-atlas-v-rocket-launch-success.html|title=Solar Orbiter launches on historic mission to study the sun's poles|access-date=4 Apr 2020|work=[[Space.com]]|author=Amy Thompson}}</ref> The laboratory is also designing part of the [[United States|US]] [[Deep Underground Neutrino Experiment]].<ref name=\":16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/194106/imperial-among-uk-institutions-building-parts/|title=Imperial among UK institutions building parts for new \u00a330m neutrino detector {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|website=Imperial News|language=en|date=November 2019|access-date=2019-11-29|last3=|first3=|last4=|first4=|last5=|first5=}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2020, immunology research at the [[Imperial College Faculty of Medicine|Faculty of Medicine]] focused on [[SARS-CoV-2]] under the leadership of Professor [[Robin Shattock]] as part of the college's [[Imperial College COVID-19 Response Team|COVID-19 Response Team]].<ref name=\":17\">{{Cite web|url=https://news.sky.com/story/coronavirus-significant-breakthrough-in-race-for-vaccine-made-by-uk-scientists-11926469|title=Coronavirus: 'Significant breakthrough' in race for vaccine made by UK scientists|website=Sky News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/195055/imperial-researchers-race-develop-coronavirus-vaccine/|title=Imperial researchers in race to develop a coronavirus vaccine {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|website=Imperial News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-06}}</ref> Professor [[Neil Ferguson (epidemiologist)|Neil Ferguson]]'s March 16 report entitled \"Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID- 19 mortality and healthcare demand\"<ref name=\"imperialcollege_Ferguson_etal_20200316\">{{Cite journal| pages = 20| last1 = Ferguson| first1 = Neil M| last2 = Laydon| first2 = Daniel| last3 = Nedjati-Gilani| first3 = Gemma| last4 = Imai| first4 = Natsuko| last5 = Ainslie| first5 = Kylie| last6 = Baguelin| first6 = Marc| last7 = Bhatia| first7 = Sangeeta| last8 = Boonyasiri| first8 = Adhiratha| last9 = Cucunub\u00e1| first9 = Zulma| last10 = Cuomo-Dannenburg| first10 = Gina| last11 = Dighe| first11 = Amy| last12 = Fu| first12 = Han| last13 = Gaythorpe| first13 = Katy| last14 = Thompson| first14 = Hayley| last15 = Verity| first15 = Robert| last16 = Volz| first16 = Erik| last17 = Wang| first17 = Haowei| last18 = Wang| first18 = Yuanrong| last19 = Walker| first19 = Patrick GT| last20 = Walters| first20 = Caroline| last21 = Winskill| first21 = Peter| last22 = Whittaker| first22 = Charles| last23 = Donnelly| first23 = Christl A| last24 = Riley| first24 = Steven| last25 = Ghani| first25 = Azra C |journal=Imperial College of Science, Technology and Medicine| title = Impact of non-pharmaceutical interventions (NPIs) to reduce COVID-19 mortality and healthcare demand| date = March 16, 2020 |url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/medicine/sph/ide/gida-fellowships/Imperial-College-COVID19-NPI-modelling-16-03-2020.pdf |access-date=March 22, 2020}}</ref> was described in a March 17 ''[[The New York Times]]''  article, as the coronavirus \"report that jarred the U.S. and the U.K. to action\".<ref name=\"NYT_Landler_20200317\">{{Cite web| title = Behind the Virus Report That Jarred the U.S. and the U.K. to Action - The New York Times| access-date = March 22, 2020 |first1= Mark |last1=Landler |first2=Stephen |last2=Castle| url = https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/17/world/europe/coronavirus-imperial-college-johnson.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Admissions ===\n{| class=\"floatright\"\n| \n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%; text-align:center; margin-bottom: 5px\"\n|+UCAS Admission Statistics\n! \n!2017\n!2016\n!2015\n!2014\n!2013\n|-\n|'''Applications'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144241/download?token=nlVZq6el|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_03 Applications by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|20,395\n|19,200\n|18,205\n|16,570\n|15,315\n|-\n|'''Offer Rate'''{{efn-lg|name=admstats1}}<ref>{{cite web|title=Sex, area background and ethnic group: I50 Imperial College London|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/145156/download?token=VpThVB-P|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|accessdate=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|43.6%\n|46.2%\n|50.7%\n|53.6%\n|54.4%\n|-\n|'''Enrols'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ucas.com/file/144196/download?token=JEpp6fiF|title=End of Cycle 2017 Data Resources DR4_001_02 Main scheme acceptances by provider|last=|first=|date=2017|website=UCAS|publisher=UCAS|access-date=25 January 2018}}</ref>\n|2,715\n|2,545\n|2,630\n|2,515\n|2,425\n|-\n|[[Yield (college admissions)|'''Yield''']]{{efn-lg|name=admstats2}}\n|30.5%\n|28.7%\n|28.5%\n|28.3%\n|29.1%\n|-\n|'''Applicant/Enrolled Ratio'''\n|7.51\n|7.54\n|6.92\n|6.59\n|6.32\n|-\n|'''[[UCAS Tariff|Average Entry Tariff]]'''{{efn-lg|name=admstats3}}<ref name=\"Complete League Table 2019\">{{cite-web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings|title=Top UK University League Table and Rankings|publisher=Complete University Guide}}</ref>\n|n/a\n|219\n|552\n|567\n|566\n|}\n{| style=\"font-size:80%;float:left\"\n|{{notelist-lg|refs=\n{{efn-lg|name=admstats1|Includes conditional offers}}\n{{efn-lg|name=admstats2|Includes candidates who failed to meet conditional offers}}\n{{efn-lg|name=admstats3|New [[UCAS Tariff]] system from 2016}}\n}}\n|}\n|}\nFor the 2018 entry, the ratio of applicants to admissions was 7.8:1 for undergraduates and 6.5:1 for postgraduates.<ref name=\":14\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/administration-and-support-services/planning/public/statistics-guides/19-08-Stats-Guide_v7.pdf|title=Statistics Pocket Guide 2018\u201319|last=|first=|date=2019|website=Imperial College London|access-date=6 November 2019}}</ref> For 2018 entry, the undergraduate courses with the lowest ratios of applicants to admissions were [[computing]] (15.4:1 ratio) followed by [[mathematics]] (10.5:1) and [[mechanical engineering]] (10.5:1).<ref name=\":14\" />The highest was [[bioengineering]] (3.8:1).<ref name=\":14\" />\n\nUndergraduates beginning their studies at Imperial in 2017\u201318 had the 4th highest average [[UCAS Tariff]] in the UK, at 205 points.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecompleteuniversityguide.co.uk/league-tables/rankings?sortby=entry-standards|title=University League Tables 2020|accessdate=1 March 2020|work=Complete University Guide}}</ref>\n\nImperial is among the most international universities in the United Kingdom,<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/best-universities/most-international-universities-world-2018|title=Most international universities in the world 2018: top 200|date=2018-03-14|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-03-19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\" /> with 50% of students from the UK, 16% of students from the EU, and 34% of students from outside the UK or EU.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/features/worlds-most-international-universities-2017|title=The World's Most International Universities 2017|date=2017-02-01|work=Times Higher Education (THE)|access-date=2018-02-10|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> The student body is 39% female and 61% male.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite web|title=Where do HE students study?|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/data-and-analysis/students/where-study#provider|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=9 February 2018}}</ref> 36.5% of Imperial's undergraduates are [[Independent school (United Kingdom)|privately educated]], the fourth highest proportion amongst mainstream British universities.<ref name=\":7\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/news/01-02-2018/widening-participation-tables|title=Widening participation: UK Performance Indicators 2016/17|website=hesa.ac.uk|publisher=Higher Education Statistics Authority|accessdate=1 February 2018}}</ref>\n\n=== Libraries ===\nThe college's [[Imperial College Central Library|Central Library]] is located on [[Queen's Lawn]] and contains the main corpus of the college's collection. It previously also housed the [[Science Museum, London|Science Museum]]'s library until 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/140906/science-museum-library-closes-prepare-research/|title=Science Museum Library closes to prepare for new research centre|last=|first=|last2=|first2=|date=|website=Imperial News|publisher=Imperial College London|language=en|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref> The Fleming library is located at [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's]] in [[Paddington]], originally the library of [[St Mary's Hospital Medical School]], with other hospital campuses also having college libraries.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/admin-services/library/use-the-library/our-libraries/|title=Our libraries|last=|first=|date=|website=imperial.ac.uk|publisher=Imperial College London|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n===Medicine===\n[[File:Alexander Fleming Building.jpg|alt=|thumb|[[Elizabeth II|Queen Elizabeth II]] opening the Alexander Fleming Building]]\n{{Main|Imperial College Faculty of Medicine|Imperial College Healthcare}}\nThe Imperial Faculty of Medicine was formed through mergers between Imperial and the St Mary's, Charing Cross and Westminster, and Royal Postgraduate medical schools and has six [[teaching hospital]]s. It accepts more than 300 undergraduate medical students per year and has around 321 taught and 700 research full-time equivalent postgraduate students.\n\n[[Imperial College Healthcare|Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust]] was formed on 1 October 2007 by the merger of Hammersmith Hospitals NHS Trust ([[Charing Cross Hospital]], [[Hammersmith Hospital]] and [[Queen Charlotte's and Chelsea Hospital]]) and St Mary's NHS Trust ([[St Mary's Hospital, London|St. Mary's Hospital]] and [[Western Eye Hospital]]) with Imperial College London Faculty of Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.nhs.uk/aboutus/index.htm |title=About us \u2013 Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust Internet |publisher=Imperial.nhs.uk |accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref> It is an academic health science centre and manages five hospitals: [[Charing Cross Hospital]], [[Queen Charlotte's and Chelsea Hospital]], [[Hammersmith Hospital]], [[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]], and [[Western Eye Hospital]]. The Trust is currently one of the largest in the UK and in 2012/13 had a turnover of \u00a3971.3 million, employed approximately 9,770 people and treated almost 1.2 million patients.<ref name=\"annrep201213\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.nhs.uk/prdcons/groups/public/@corporate/@communications/documents/doc/id_040038.pdf|title=Annual Report 2012/13|accessdate=28 April 2013|publisher=Imperial College Healthcare NHS Trust|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141222133347/http://www.imperial.nhs.uk/prdcons/groups/public/@corporate/@communications/documents/doc/id_040038.pdf|archivedate=22 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOther (non-academic health science centres) hospitals affiliated with Imperial College include [[Chelsea and Westminster Hospital]], [[Royal Brompton Hospital]], [[West Middlesex University Hospital]], [[Hillingdon Hospital]], [[Mount Vernon Hospital]], [[Harefield Hospital]], [[Ealing Hospital]], [[Central Middlesex Hospital]], [[Northwick Park Hospital]], [[St Mark's Hospital]], St Charles' Hospital and [[St Peter's Hospital, Chertsey|St Peter's Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Meet the Council |url=http://www.chelwest.nhs.uk/foundationtrust/members_council/meetTheCouncil.html |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090706070615/http://www.chelwest.nhs.uk/foundationtrust/members_council/meetTheCouncil.html |publisher=Chelsea and Westminster NHS Foundation Trust |archivedate=6 July 2009 |accessdate=14 September 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" perrow=\"6\" heights=\"110\">\nFile:St Mary's Hospital 02.jpg|[[St Mary's Hospital, London|St Mary's Hospital]]\nFile:Charing Cross Hospital in London, spring 2013 (2).JPG|[[Charing Cross Hospital]]\nFile:Chelsea & Westminster Hospital July 2013.JPG|[[Chelsea and Westminster Hospital]]\nFile:Royal Brompton Hospital-geograph-2105200.jpg|[[Royal Brompton Hospital]]\nFile:Hammersmith Hospital, London in spring 2013 (1).JPG|[[Hammersmith Hospital]]\n</gallery>\n\n== Controversies ==\n\n=== Accusations of bullying ===\nIn 2003, it was reported that one third of female academics \"believe that discrimination or bullying by managers has held back their careers\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/uk/2003/apr/18/highereducation.education|title=Female staff 'feel bullied' at Imperial College|accessdate=6 December 2014|newspaper=The Guardian|date=2003-04-18|last1=Woodward|first1=Will|last2=Editor|first2=Education}}</ref> Imperial has since won the Athena SWAN Award, which recognises employment practices that are supportive of the careers of women in science, technology, engineering and maths.\n\nIn 2007, concerns were raised about the methods that were being used to fire people in the Faculty of Medicine.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/crude-recipe-for-a-chicken-run-sector/209175.article|title=Crude recipe for a 'chicken-run' sector|accessdate=6 December 2014|date=2007-05-31}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal | last = Colquhoun | first = David | year = 2007 | title = How to get good science. | journal = Physiology News | volume = 69 | pages = 12\u201314 | url = http://dcscience.net/colquhoun-goodscience-jp-version-2007.pdf }}</ref> However, in 2014, [[Stefan Grimm]], of the Department of Medicine, was found dead after being threatened with dismissal for failure to raise enough grant money.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/imperial-college-london-to-review-procedures-after-death-of-academic/2017188.article |title=Imperial College London to 'review procedures' after death of academic|accessdate=6 December 2014|date=2014-11-27}}</ref> His last email before his passing accused his employers of bullying by demanding that he should get grants worth at least \u00a3200,000 per year.<ref name=\"blog\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dcscience.net/2014/12/01/publish-and-perish-at-imperial-college-london-the-death-of-stefan-grimm|title=Publish ''and'' perish at Imperial College London: the death of Stefan Grimm|accessdate=6 December 2014|date=December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/news/imperial-college-professor-stefan-grimm-was-given-grant-income-target/2017369.article|title=Imperial College professor Stefan Grimm 'was given grant income target'|accessdate=6 December 2014|date=2014-12-03}}</ref> The college announced an internal inquiry into Stefan Grimm's death, and found that the performance metrics for his position were unreasonable, with new metrics for performance being needed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/news/stefan-grimm-inquest-new-policies-may-not-have-prevented-suicide/2019563.article|title=Stefan Grimm inquest: new policies may not have prevented suicide|date=9 April 2015|newspaper=Times Higher Education (THE)|language=en|access-date=23 January 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Student life==\n\n===Student body===\nFor the {{HESA year}} academic year, Imperial had a total full-time student body of {{HESA student population|INSTID=0132}}, consisting of {{HESA undergraduate population|INSTID=0132}} undergraduate students and {{HESA postgraduate population|INSTID=0132}} postgraduates.<ref name=\"HESA citation\"/> 50.7% of the student body is from outside of the UK.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.timeshighereducation.com/student/news/world-ranked-universities-most-international-students|title=World-ranked universities with the most international students|accessdate=30 September 2015|work=Times Higher Education}}</ref> 32% of all full-time students came from outside the [[European Union]] in 2013\u201314,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/pressOffice/sfr210/071277_student_sfr210_1314_table_3.xlsx|title=2013/14 Students by HE provider, level, mode and domicile|publisher=[[Higher Education Statistics Agency]]|accessdate=8 November 2015|format=XLSX|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303231845/https://www.hesa.ac.uk/dox/pressOffice/sfr210/071277_student_sfr210_1314_table_3.xlsx|archivedate=3 March 2016|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and around 13% of the International students had Chinese nationality in 2007\u201308.<ref name=\"statscard 2010\" /> \n\nImperial's male to female ratio for undergraduate students is uneven at approximately 64:36 overall<ref name=\"statscard 2010\" /> and 5:1 or higher in some engineering courses. However, medicine has an approximate 1:1 ratio with biology degrees tending to be higher.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.unistats.com |title=Search best UK universities, make university comparisons and see student satisfaction ratings and UCAS points |publisher=Unistats |accessdate=23 March 2011}}</ref>\n\n{{wide image|Imperial College - South Kensington Campus.jpg|600px|[[Queen's Lawn]] at South Kensington Campus}}\n\n===Imperial College Union===\n[[Imperial College Union]] is the [[students' union]] and is run by five full-time [[sabbatical]] officers elected from the student body for a tenure of one year, and a number of permanent members of staff. It is split into constituent unions aligned with the faculties of the college, carrying on the association with the original constituent colleges of Imperial, the [[Royal College of Science Union]], [[Imperial College Faculty of Engineering#City and Guilds College Union|City and Guilds College Union]], [[Royal School of Mines#RSM Student.27s Union|Royal School of Mines Student's Union]] and [[Imperial College School of Medicine Students' Union]]. The Union is given a large subvention by the university, much of which is spent on maintaining over 300 clubs, projects and societies.<ref>{{cite web |author=Dave Parry |url=http://www.union.ic.ac.uk/money/FinanceFiles/list.shtml |title=Imperial College Union |publisher=Union.ic.ac.uk |accessdate=16 June 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060430052412/http://www.union.ic.ac.uk/money/FinanceFiles/list.shtml |archivedate=30 April 2006 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Examples of notable student groups and projects are [[InterVol|Project Nepal]] which sends Imperial College students to work on educational development programmes in rural Nepal<ref>{{cite web|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/archive/IC_2011/2011_1504_A.pdf |title=Felix : The student voice of Imperial College London |publisher=Felixonline.co.uk |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> and [[El Salvador Project|the El Salvador Project]], a construction based project in Central America.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elsalvadorproject.org.uk/2012/sponsors.html |title=Sponsors |publisher=Elsalvadorproject.org.uk |date= |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> The Union also hosts sports-related clubs such as [[Imperial College Boat Club]] and [[Imperial College Gliding Club]].\n\nThe Union operates on two sites, with most events at the Union Building on [[Beit Hall|Beit Quad]] at South Kensington, with mostly [[Imperial College School of Medicine|medical school]] events at the Reynold's bar, [[Charing Cross Hospital|Charing Cross]].\n\n=== Facilities ===\n[[File:Ethos Gym.jpg|alt=|thumb|Ethos Gym]]\nSports facilities at Imperial's London campuses include four gyms, including the main Ethos gym at the South Kensington Campus, two swimming pools and two sports halls.<ref>{{cite web|author=Imperial College London |url=http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/sports/facilities |title=Imperial College Sports Facilities |publisher=imperial.ac.uk |accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref> Imperial has additional sports facilities at the Heston and Harlington sports grounds.\n\nOn the South Kensington campus, there are a total of six music practice rooms which consist of upright pianos for usage by people of any grade, and grand pianos which are exclusively for people who have achieved Grade 8 or above.<ref>{{cite web|author=Imperial College London |url=http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/arts/blythcentre/facilities/practicefacilities |title=Imperial College Music Facilities |publisher=imperial.ac.uk |accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nThere are two student bars on the South Kensington campus, one at the [[Imperial College Union]] and one at Eastside.<ref>{{cite web|author=Imperial College Union |url=http://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/food-drink/ |title=Food and Drink|publisher=imperialcollegeunion.org |accessdate=21 March 2012}}</ref>\nThere are a number of pubs and bars on campus and also surrounding the campus, which become a popular social activity for Imperial's students. The [[Pewter]] tankard collection at Imperial College Union is the largest in Europe, with the majority of clubs and societies having tankards associated with their clubs.<ref>{{cite web |title= Questions about Tankards |url= https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/food-drink/union-bar/questions-about-tankards |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20170523182226/https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/food-drink/union-bar/questions-about-tankards |archivedate= 23 May 2017 |df= dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Imperial College Farmers Market, Prince's Gardens.png|thumb|The weekly college farmer's market]]\n\n=== Student media ===\n'''Imperial College Radio'''<br />\n[[Imperial College Radio]] (ICRadio) was founded in November 1975 with the intention of broadcasting to the student [[Dormitory|halls of residence]] from a studio under Southside, actually commencing broadcasts in late 1976. It now broadcasts from the West Basement of Beit Quad [[web radio|over the internet]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.icradio.com/ |title=Imperial College Radio, London, UK |publisher=Icradio.com |accessdate=16 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n'''Imperial College TV'''\n\nImperial College TV (ICTV) is Imperial College Union's TV station, founded in 1969 and operated from a small TV studio in the Electrical Engineering block. The department had bought an early [[AMPEX]] [[Type A videotape|Type A 1-inch videotape recorder]] and this was used to produce an occasional short news programme which was then played to students by simply moving the VTR and a monitor into a common room. A cable link to the Southside halls of residence was laid in a tunnel under Exhibition Road in 1972. Besides the news, early productions included a film of the Queen opening what was then called College Block.\n\n'''Felix Newspaper'''\n\n''[[Felix (newspaper)|Felix]]'' is weekly student newspaper, first released on 9 December 1949.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ic.ac.uk/centenary/timeline/1940.shtml|title=Imperial College \u2013 Centenary website \u2013 Timeline \u2013 1940\u20131949|website=ic.ac.uk}}</ref> In addition to news, Felix also carries comic strips, features, opinions, puzzles and reviews, plus reports of trips and Imperial College sporting events.\n\n===Student societies===\n[[File:RGETeam.jpg|thumb|[[Racing Green Endurance]] is a student-led project to demonstrate the potential of zero-emission cars.]]\n\n'''Imperial College Boat Club'''\n\nThe [[Imperial College Boat Club]] is the rowing club of Imperial and was founded on 12 December 1919. The college's boat house is located in [[Putney]] on the [[River Thames|Thames]], and was recently refurbished, reopening in 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/admin-services/estates-projects/construction-projects/completed-projects/putney-boathouse-development/|title=Putney Boathouse development\u200c|website=Imperial College London|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref> The club has a number of notable accolades, such as three alumni of the college in the gold medal winning GB 8+ at the [[2000 Sydney Olympics]], along with their coach Martin McElroy. The club has been highly successful, with many wins at Henley Royal Regatta.\n\n'''Sports'''\n\nImperial College has over 60 sports clubs<ref name=AtoZSports>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperialcollegeunion.org/activities/a-to-z|title=Imperial College Union A to Z of Societies|website=Imperial College Union|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-02-24}}</ref>, of which many participate in the [[British Universities and Colleges Sport]] Association leagues such as [[British Universities American Football League|American Football]], [[University and College Rugby League|Rugby]], Badminton, [[Lacrosse_in_England#Men's_lacrosse|Lacrosse]], [[BUCS Football League|Football]], Ice Hockey, and many others.<ref name=AtoZSports/> \n\n'''Exploration Club'''\n\nImperial's Exploration Board was established in 1957 to assist students with a desire for exploration. Trips have included Afghanistan, Alaska, Cameroon, Ethiopia, Fiji, the Himalayas, Iran, Morocco, Norway, Tanzania, Thailand, Ukraine, and the Yukon.<ref>{{cite web|title=Exploration Club|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/history/college-developments/|website=A timeline of College Developments}}</ref>\n\n'''Dramatic Society'''<br />\nThe Imperial College Dramatic Society (DramSoc<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dramsoc.org/|title=DramSoc|website=DramSoc|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref>) is one of two major theatrical arts societies, with the other being the Musical Theatre Society, and it was founded in 1912.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dramatic Changes|url=http://felixonline.co.uk/issuearchive/issue/367/download/|accessdate=28 June 2015|agency=Felix Newspaper|issue=371|date=9 December 1974}}</ref> The society puts on three major plays each year, in addition to several smaller fringe productions. It is additionally one the London-based dramatic societies to participate in the London Student Drama Festival,<ref>{{cite web|title=London Student Drama Festival|url=http://ucludrama.org.uk/london-student-drama-festival-2/|website=UCLU Drama|publisher=UCLU Drama Society|accessdate=28 June 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150701102125/http://ucludrama.org.uk/london-student-drama-festival-2/|archivedate=1 July 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> and regularly attends the [[Edinburgh Fringe]]. DramSoc is responsible for the day-to-day maintenance of the Union's theatrical space, the [[Union Concert Hall]].\n\n===Student housing===\n[[File:Beit12.jpg|thumb|[[Beit Hall]]]]\n[[File:Prince's Gardens Halls.png|thumb|220px|Prince's Gardens, surrounded by college halls of residence]]\nImperial College owns and manages twenty-one halls of residence in [[Inner London]], [[Acton, London|Acton]], and [[Ascot, Berkshire|Ascot]]. Over three thousand rooms are available, guaranteeing first year undergraduates a place in College residences.\n\nThe majority of halls offer single or twin accommodation with some rooms having [[Bathroom|en suite]] facilities. Bedrooms are provided with basic furniture and with access to shared kitchens and bathrooms. All rooms come with internet access and access to the Imperial network.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/media/imperial-college/current-students/accommodation/public/College-Accommodation-Licence-19-20.pdf|title=College Accommodation Licence (2019\u20132020)}}</ref> Most of them are considered among the newest student halls at London universities.\n\nMost students in college or university accommodation are first-year undergraduates, as they are granted a room once they have selected Imperial as their firm offer with [[UCAS]]. The majority of older students and postgraduates find accommodation in the private sector, help for which is provided by the college private housing office. However a handful of students may continue to live in halls in later years if they take the position of a \"hall senior\", and places are available for a small number of returning students in the Evelyn Garden halls.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/study/campus-life/accommodation/halls/returning-students-accommodation/ | title=Accommodation for returning students}}</ref> Some students also live in [[International Students House, London]].\n\nList of Halls of Residence:<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/study/campus-life/accommodation/halls/ug/ | title=Undergraduate halls}}</ref> {{divcol}}\n* South Kensington\n** [[Beit Hall]]\n** Eastside Halls\n*** Linstead Hall\n*** Gabor Hall\n*** Wilkinson Hall\n** Southside Halls\n*** Falmouth Hall\n*** Selkirk Hall\n*** Tizard Hall\n*** Keogh Hall\n* Evelyn Gardens\n** Holbein Hall\n** Southwell Hall\n** Willis Jackson Hall\n* Parsons House\n* Pembridge Hall\n* Putney Boathouse\n* [[Wilson House, London|Wilson House]]\n* Woodward Buildings\n* Xenia\n{{divcolend}}\n\n== Notable alumni, faculty and staff ==\n{{Main|List of Nobel laureates affiliated with Imperial College London|List of Imperial College London people|President of Imperial College London}}\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:Cyril Norman Hinshelwood Nobel.jpg|Sir [[Cyril Norman Hinshelwood]]\nFile:Professor Abdus Salam.gif|[[Abdus Salam]]\nFile:Alexander Fleming 3.jpg|Sir [[Alexander Fleming]]\nFile:Blackett.jpg|[[Patrick Blackett, Baron Blackett]]\nFile:Sir William Crookes 1906.jpg|Sir [[William Crookes]]\nFile:Thomas Henry Huxley - Project Gutenberg eText 16935.jpg|[[Thomas Huxley]]\nFile:John Pendry 2014b.jpg|Sir [[John Pendry]]\nFile:Portrait of H. G. Wells.jpg|[[H.G. Wells]]\nFile:Geoffrey Wilkinson (ca. 1976).jpg|[[Geoffrey Wilkinson]]\nFile:Dame_Sally_Davies_FMedSci_DBE_FRS.jpg|Dame [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Sally Davies]]\nFile:Brian-May_with_red_special.jpg|[[Brian May]] CBE\nFile:Nobel_Prize_24_2013.jpg|[[Peter Higgs]]\nFile:Lord_Winston_2011_(Portrait).jpg|[[Robert Winston]]\nFile:Professor_Martin_Hairer_FRS.jpg|[[Martin Hairer]]\n</gallery>\nNobel laureates: (medicine) [[Alexander Fleming|Sir Alexander Fleming]], [[Ernst Boris Chain|Sir Ernst Boris Chain]], [[Frederick Gowland Hopkins|Sir Frederick Gowland Hopkins]], [[Andrew Huxley|Sir Andrew Fielding Huxley]], [[Rodney Robert Porter]], (physics) [[Abdus Salam]], [[George Paget Thomson|Sir George Paget Thomson]], [[Patrick Blackett, Baron Blackett]], [[Dennis Gabor]], [[Peter Higgs]], (chemistry) [[Norman Haworth|Sir Norman Haworth]], [[Cyril Norman Hinshelwood|Sir Cyril Norman Hinshelwood]], [[Derek Barton|Sir Derek Barton]], [[Geoffrey Wilkinson|Sir Geoffrey Wilkinson]], [[George Porter|Sir George Porter]].<ref name=\"Imperial.ac.uk\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/introducing-imperial/our-people/award-winners/|title=Award winners &#124; Imperial College London|date=|publisher=Imperial.ac.uk|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>\n\nFields medalists: [[Klaus Roth|Klaus Friedrich Roth]], [[Simon Donaldson|Sir Simon Donaldson]], [[Martin Hairer]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/about/introducing-imperial/our-people/award-winners/fields-medallists/|title=Fields medallists|website=Imperial College London|language=en-GB|access-date=2018-07-13}}</ref>\n\nAcademic affiliations include: [[Tom W. B. Kibble|Sir Tom Kibble]], co-discoverer of [[Higgs Boson]];<ref>\u2018KIBBLE, Sir Thomas (Walter Bannerman)\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U23025 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Tejinder Virdee|Sir Tejinder Virdee]], experimental particle physicist;<ref>\u2018VIRDEE, Sir Tejinder Singh\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U257519 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[John Pendry|Sir John Pendry]], theoretical solid state physicist;<ref>\u2018PENDRY, Sir John (Brian)\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U30495 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Sir Christopher Kelk Ingold]], physical organic chemistry pioneer;<ref>\u2018INGOLD, Sir Christopher (Keik)\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U53971 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[William Henry Perkin|Sir William Henry Perkin]], discoverer of the first synthetic organic chemical dye [[mauveine]];<ref>\u2018PERKIN, Sir William Henry\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2015 ; online edn, Feb 2015 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U189845 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Sir Edward Frankland]], originator of the theory of [[valency (chemistry)|chemical valency]];<ref>\u2018FRANKLAND, Sir Edward\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U186130 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Sir William Crookes]], discoverer of [[thallium]];<ref>\u2018CROOKES, Prof. Sir William\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U195207 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Sir Alan Fersht]], chemist;<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Fersht, Sir Alan (Roy), (born 21 April 1943), Herchel Smith Professor of Organic Chemistry, University of Cambridge, 1988\u20132010; Fellow, since 1988, and Master, 2012\u201318, Gonville and Caius College, Cambridge; Hon. Director, Cambridge Centre for Protein Engineering (formerly MRC Unit for Protein Function and Design), 1989\u20132010; Emeritus Group Leader, MRC Laboratory of Molecular Biology, Cambridge, since 2010 |date=December 1, 2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U15668 |title=Who's Who }}</ref> [[David Phillips (chemist)|David Phillips]], chemist;<ref>{{cite book |chapter=Phillips, Prof. David, (born 3 Dec. 1939), Professor of Physical Chemistry, 1989\u20132006, Hofmann Professor of Chemistry, 1999\u20132006, now Professor Emeritus, and Dean, Faculties of Life Sciences and Physical Sciences, 2002\u201306, Imperial College London |date=December 1, 2018 |publisher=Oxford University Press |doi=10.1093/ww/9780199540884.013.U30743 |title=Who's Who }}</ref> [[Harold Hopkins (physicist)|Harold Hopkins]], contributed to the theory and design of optical instruments;<ref>\u2018HOPKINS, Prof. Harold Horace\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U173215 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Alfred North Whitehead]], mathematician and philosopher;<ref>\u2018WHITEHEAD, Alfred North\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U233372 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Steven Cowley|Sir Steven Cowley]], physicist and president of [[Corpus Christi College, Oxford]];<ref>\u2018COWLEY, Prof. Steven\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U261946 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> and Sir [[John Ambrose Fleming]], inventor of the [[vacuum tube]].<ref>\u2018FLEMING, Sir (John) Ambrose\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U225450 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref>\n\nIn biology and medicine; [[Thomas Henry Huxley|Thomas Huxley]], advocate of the theory of evolution; [[Wendy Barclay]], virologist; [[Sally Davies (doctor)|Dame Sally Davies]], the [[Chief Medical Officer (United Kingdom)|Chief Medical Officer]] for England;<ref>Davies, Dame Sally (Claire), WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO. Retrieved 27 Dec. 2017, from http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-13126.</ref> [[David Livingstone]], medical missionary and [[Clare Lloyd]], biologist.\nIn engineering; [[Chi Onwurah]], politician;<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/188594/mp-chi-onwurah-as-engineer-often/|title=MP Chi Onwurah: \"As an engineer, I was often the only Black person in the room\" {{!}} Imperial News {{!}} Imperial College London|work=Imperial News|access-date=2018-11-10|language=en-GB}}</ref> [[Julia Higgins|Dame Julia Higgins]], polymer scientist;<ref>Higgins, Dame Julia (Stretton), WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO. Retrieved 27 Dec. 2017, from http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-20092.</ref> [[Judith Hackitt|Dame Judith Hackitt]], former Chair of the [[Health and Safety Executive]];<ref>Hackitt, Dame Judith (Elizabeth), WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO. Retrieved 27 Dec. 2017, from http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-151505.</ref> [[Dudley Maurice Newitt]], scientific director of the [[Special Operations Executive]];<ref>Newitt, Dudley Maurice, WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO. Retrieved 27 Dec. 2017, from http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540891.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-157958.</ref> and [[Julia King, Baroness Brown of Cambridge]], engineer and Member of the House of Lords.<ref>Brown of Cambridge, Baroness, (Julia Elizabeth King), WHO'S WHO & WHO WAS WHO. Retrieved 27 Dec. 2017, from http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/10.1093/ww/9780199540884.001.0001/ww-9780199540884-e-41612.</ref>\n\nNon-academic affiliations include: [[H. G. Wells]], author;<ref>{{cite book |last1=Parrinder |first1=Patrick |chapter=Wells, Herbert George (1866\u20131946), novelist and social commentator |title=Oxford Dictionary of National Biography |date=January 6, 2011 |publisher=Oxford University Press |doi=10.1093/ref:odnb/36831 }}</ref> [[Nikolas Tombazis]], chief car designer at [[McLaren]] and [[Scuderia Ferrari|Ferrari]]; [[Ralph Robins]], CEO of [[Rolls-Royce Motor Cars|Rolls-Royce]];<ref>\u2018ROBINS, Sir Ralph (Harry)\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U32829 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Brian May]], guitarist of rock band [[Queen (band)|Queen]];<ref>\u2018MAY, Dr Brian Harold\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U247368 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Chew Choon Seng]], CEO of [[Singapore Airlines]]; Sir [[Julius Vogel]], former [[Prime Minister of New Zealand]];<ref>\u2018VOGEL, Hon. Sir Julius\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U191871 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Rajiv Gandhi]], [[Prime Minister of India]];<ref>\u2018GANDHI, Rajiv\u2019, Who Was Who, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 1920\u20132016; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2014 ; online edn, April 2014 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whowaswho/U172595 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Teo Chee Hean]], [[Deputy Prime Minister of Singapore]]; [[Huw Thomas (physician)|Huw Thomas]], [[Physician to the Queen]];<ref>\u2018THOMAS, Prof. Huw Jeremy Wyndham\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U282180 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> Sir [[Roger Bannister]], ran the first [[four-minute mile]];<ref>\u2018BANNISTER, Sir Roger (Gilbert)\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U6405 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[David Warren (inventor)|David Warren]], inventor of the [[flight data recorder]] and [[cockpit voice recorder]];<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-49012771|title=This little-known inventor has probably saved your life|website=BBC News}}</ref> [[Andreas Mogensen]], first Danish astronaut; [[David Pearson (computer scientist)|David Pearson]], software engineer; [[Winston Wong]], entrepreneur; [[Alan Howard (hedge fund manager)|Alan Howard]], hedge fund manager and philanthropist; [[Cyrus Pallonji Mistry]], former chairman of the [[Tata Group]];<ref>\u2018MISTRY, Cyrus Pallonji\u2019, Who's Who 2017, A & C Black, an imprint of Bloomsbury Publishing plc, 2017; online edn, Oxford University Press, 2016 ; online edn, Nov 2016 [http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U268705 accessed 2 April 2017]</ref> [[Michael Birch (businessman)|Michael Birch]], entrepreneur; [[Henry Charles Stephens]], politician; Sir [[Michael Uren]], businessman and philanthropist; [[Ian Read]], CEO of [[Pfizer]], [[Pallab Ghosh]], BBC correspondent, [[Hannah Devlin]], science journalist.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|size=small|London}}\n* [[Albertopolis]]\n* [[Education in London]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{NoteFoot}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist\n|refs =\n<!--ref name=nobel>{{cite web|url=http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/aboutimperial/imperial_people/nobel_laureates|title=Nobel Laureates associated with Imperial College|accessdate=4 October 2010|publisher=Imperial College London}}</ref-->\n\n<!--ref name=fields>{{cite web|url=http://www3.imperial.ac.uk/aboutimperial/imperial_people/fieldsmedallists|title=Fields Medalists associated with Imperial College|accessdate=24 October 2010|publisher=Imperial College London}}</ref-->\n\n<!--<ref name=\"timeline\">{{cite web|url=http://www.imperial.